~~~C++
    const auto l = len(ucodes);
    for (auto i = 0; i < l; ++i)
    {
        using namespace boost::python;

        const object t = ucodes[i];
        extract<unsigned> num{t};
        if (num.check())
        {
            // ... Do something with num()
        }
        else
        {
            extract<tuple> er{t};
            if (!er.check())
            {
                PyErr_SetObject(PyExc_RuntimeError, t.ptr());
                return;
            }
            const auto range = er();
            // ... Do something with extract<unsigned>{range[0]}() and extract<unsigned>{range[1]}()
        }
    }
~~~
where `ucodes` is a function argument of type `const boost::python::list &`

According to [Docs » Python C++ interface » Python types](https://pybind11.readthedocs.io/en/stable/advanced/pycpp/object.html?highlight=cast_error), the best I can do is
~~~C++
    const auto l = len(ucodes);
    for (std::remove_cv_t<decltype(l)> i = 0; i < l; ++i)
    {
        const auto t = ucodes[i];
        try
        {
            auto num = py::cast<unsigned>(t);
            // ... Do something with num()
        }
        catch (const py::cast_error &) // this one
        {
            try
            {
                auto range = py::cast<py::tuple>(t);
                // ... Do something with py::cast<unsigned>(range[0]) and py::cast<unsigned>(range[1])
            }
            catch (const py::cast_error &e)
            {
                PyErr_SetString(PyExc_RuntimeError, e.what());
                return;
            }
        }
    }
~~~
Is there a way to not catch `py::cast_error`, particularly the first one?

#### Issue description

I haven't actually tested it, but this bit of code in pytypes.h looks a lot like a memory leak:
```c++
Py_buffer *view = new Py_buffer();
if (PyObject_GetBuffer(m_ptr, view, flags) != 0)
    throw error_already_set();
return buffer_info(view);
```
In the success case, the returned buffer_info owns `view`, but in the failure case `view` simply leaks.

In gitlab by @sylvaingaudan on Aug 11, 2017, 08:09

Every `GET`/`POST` service used for retrieving data (read only services) should implement the cache control that is already referenced in the API:
```java
@ApiParam(value = "max-age-cache", required = false)
@QueryParam(value = "max-age-cache") Integer maxagecache
```
This is done by setting the cache control on the response, if provided:
```java
Reponse reponse = Response.ok(...);
if(DEFAULT_MAX_AGE_CACHE!=null || maxagecache!=null){
   if(maxagecache == null){
      maxagecache=DEFAULT_MAX_AGE_CACHE;// DEFAULT_MAX_AGE_CACHE defined in ARLAS configuration file
   }
   CacheControl cc = new CacheControl();
   cc.setPrivate(false);
   cc.setNoCache(false);
   cc.setNoTransform(true);
   cc.setMaxAge(maxagecache);
   reponse.cacheControl(cc);
}
return reponse.build();
```

